Hey! So, unfortunately, I have been dealing with a tough diagnosis since December 20th. I underwent an almost 7 hour emergency surgery on January 4th. It's been a very difficult journey for Sofia, my family, and close friends who have been there for me. I'm a "let's get this handled" type of person. With that said, I'm getting this handled. It will be a long journey, but through it all, I will be diligent, and by the grace of God, I will come out of this cancer free. 

Hearing you have a late stage cancer (Ovarian Cancer Stage 3) can be insanely scary. I only have one option here, live life every day to the fullest (even when I feel like crap) and do the best I can. 

As for my business, I'm sure a lot of clients & colleagues are shocked. We didn't miss a beat. A good team will shine during times like these! Business as per usual, and yes, I am still working 💪 🏡

I appreciate all of the love and encouragement and again could not have made it this far without Sofia, my family, friends, and amazing support system. 

Next up, it's Chemo time! 🙏🏻❤️

As posted on @su2c 🏳️‍🌈
This #PrideMonth, we’re spotlighting a group of friends united in their support as one navigates a cancer diagnosis. ❤️

Nikki Weiss-Goldstein and Rose Garcia -- along with the other cast members Mikey Koffman, Whitney Mixter, Tracy Ryerson, and Jill Sloane Goldstein -- formed a friendship on the docuseries The Real L Word, and now have come back together to support Rose who was diagnosed with stage 3 ovarian cancer in December 2022.

The group has and continues to support Rose in many ways. Fellow cancer survivor, Nikki, has been there for Rose by introducing her personal oncological nurse practitioner to navigate Rose's diagnosis and care. Jill says, "As her friends, we will fight alongside of her. We will lift her up when she's feeling low, hold her hand when she's feeling overwhelmed and revel in appreciation when the cancer is in her rearview. We all know she's not one to mess with!"

Nikki advises her fellow members of the LGBTQ+ community and anyone facing cancer to remember to bring loved ones to appointments, always get a second opinion, and have hope in cancer research. Nikki closes with, “Cancer is not a club that any of us want to belong, but if Rose and I have collectively helped save lives through our own journey, we are very grateful.” 

Photo credit: Molly Adams
